Hi Chad!


&gt; I am writing a test related to XML parsing.  In the setUp() of my test, I read 
&gt; an InputStream as follows:
&gt; 
&gt;    inputStream = this.getClass().getResourceAsStream(&quot;sample.xml&quot;);
&gt; 
&gt; ...where sample.xml is in the same directory as my TestCase.
&gt; 
&gt; I then have a &quot;sanity&quot; check test to make sure I read the InputStream correctly:
&gt; 
&gt;    public void testSampleInputStreamIsValid() {
&gt;      assertNotNull(&quot;InputStream should not be null&quot;, inputStream);
&gt;    }
&gt; 
&gt; When I run this from within my IDE (Eclipse), it works fine - whether I run the 
&gt; test directly, or from a suite (which is in another package).
Eclipse copies your resources to your classpath for you.
# it wouldn&#39;t be much of an IDE if it didn&#39;t, huh?

&gt; HOWEVER, whenever I run it from Ant or Maven, I get a failure (InputStream is null).
Now it&#39;s your responsibility.

Here&#39;s a sample ant build.xml extract that I&#39;m using right now:

  &lt;target name=&quot;compile&quot; description=&quot;compile product code&quot;&gt;
    &lt;mkdir dir=&quot;${java.build.dir}&quot; /&gt;
    &lt;!-- compile the code --&gt;
    &lt;javac destdir=&quot;${java.build.dir}&quot;&gt;
      &lt;src path=&quot;${java.src.dir}&quot; /&gt;
    &lt;/javac&gt;
    &lt;!-- copy the resources --&gt;
    &lt;copy todir=&quot;${java.build.dir}&quot;&gt;
      &lt;fileset dir=&quot;${java.src.dir}&quot;&gt;
        &lt;exclude name=&quot;**/*.java&quot;/&gt;
      &lt;/fileset&gt;
    &lt;/copy&gt;
  &lt;/target&gt;

for maven, you can associate resources with the &lt;resources&gt; tag:

    &lt;unitTest&gt;
      &lt;includes&gt;
        &lt;include&gt;**/*Test.java&lt;/include&gt;
      &lt;/includes&gt;
      &lt;resources&gt;
        &lt;resource&gt;
          &lt;directory&gt;src/test&lt;/directory&gt;
          &lt;includes&gt;
            &lt;include&gt;**/*.xml&lt;/include&gt;
          &lt;/includes&gt;
        &lt;/resource&gt;
      &lt;/resources&gt;
    &lt;/unitTest&gt;

I think you&#39;ll get the picture.


Good luck!

